message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The presence of HBsAb (hepatitis B surface antibody) indicates immunity to the hepatitis B virus, as it is produced in response to the virus or the hepatitis B vaccine. HBsAg, HBcAb, and HBeAg are all markers of active hepatitis B infection or exposure.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Among the options, only HBsAb (Hepatitis B surface antibody) indicates immunity to the virus. HBsAg (Hepatitis B surface antigen) indicates active infection or carrier state, HBcAb (Hepatitis B core antibody) indicates exposure to the virus, and HBeAg (Hepatitis B e antigen) indicates active viral replication and high infectivity.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. HBsAb is the serologic marker for immunity to hepatitis B virus, as it indicates the presence of antibodies against the virus. HBsAg is the surface antigen of the virus, and a positive result indicates current infection. HBcAb is the core antigen of the virus, and its presence indicates a past or present infection. HBeAg is the e antigen of the virus, and its presence indicates active viral replication and increased infectivity.
